#compdef xwayland-satellite
# Documentation: source-direct extraction from upstream
# Supreeeme/xwayland-satellite src/main.rs —
#   parse_args() at lines 94-247 (the hand-rolled argv match
#     dispatcher; NO clap despite being a Rust binary)
#   ParsedFlags struct at lines 31-58 (the state machine for
#     accumulated flag values)
#   ParsedFlags::to_vec() at lines 60-91 (the actual Xwayland
#     command-line that this wrapper produces internally)
#   essential-extension whitelist at line 148 (the 4 extensions
#     that cannot be disabled via -extension)
# Reference accessed: 2026-05-30 via gh api.
#
# xwayland-satellite is the **XWayland-on-non-XWayland-compositor
# bridge** — runs an unmodified Xwayland server as a satellite
# process under any Wayland compositor that lacks built-in
# XWayland support.  THE canonical XWayland solution for R220's
# niri compositor (already in the corpus) and other minimalist
# Wayland compositors.  Sister tool to niri / wlroots-based
# compositors.
#
# Critical extraction note: xwayland-satellite uses **X.org-
# style single-dash long-form flags** (-ac, -audit, -auth, etc.)
# rather than GNU getopt double-dash flags — intentional for
# CLI compatibility with Xwayland's own flag syntax so existing
# scripts can be reused.  Only ONE flag uses double-dash:
# `--test-listenfd-support` (line 227).
#
# Critical extraction note: 4 X extensions are HARDCODED as
# essential and CANNOT be disabled via `-extension NAME` —
# attempts are silently ignored (main.rs line 148):
#   COMPOSITE | RANDR | XFIXES | X-Resource
# Documented in the completion comment block so users
# understand why some `-extension` invocations are no-ops.
#
# Critical extraction note: parse_args() does NOT use clap or
# any parser library despite being a Rust binary — it's a
# hand-rolled `while let Some(arg) = args.next()` match
# dispatcher.  This means flag parsing is strictly positional
# (no `--flag=VALUE` syntax — only `--flag VALUE` with space
# separation) and unknown flags PANIC the process (line 241
# `panic!("Unrecognized argument: {arg}")`).
#
# Critical extraction note: `-verbose` has dual-mode behavior at
# line 228-235 — `-verbose 3` parses the next arg as u32 and
# sets verbosity to 3; `-verbose` alone (or followed by a
# non-numeric token) INCREMENTS the current verbosity by 1.
# This matches Xwayland's own behavior.

_arguments \
  '-help[print usage and exit]' \
  '-version[print xwayland-satellite version and exit]' \
  '--test-listenfd-support[probe-mode: exit 0 if -listenfd is supported]' \
  '-ac[disable access control restrictions]' \
  '-audit+[set audit trail level]:level:' \
  '-auth+[X authority file (pass only once — multiple -auth flags panic)]:file:_files' \
  '-core[generate core dump of Xwayland on fatal error]' \
  \*'+extension+[enable X server extension (repeatable)]:name:' \
  \*'-extension+[disable X server extension (repeatable; cannot disable COMPOSITE|RANDR|XFIXES|X-Resource)]:name:' \
  '-glamor+[use given API for Glamor acceleration]:api:(gl es none)' \
  \*'-listen+[listen on protocol (repeatable; e.g. tcp, unix)]:protocol:' \
  \*'-nolisten+[do not listen on protocol (repeatable)]:protocol:' \
  \*'-listenfd+[add given fd as listen socket (repeatable; each fd unique)]:fd:' \
  '*-verbose+[verbose startup messages (repeatable to increment; numeric arg sets level)]:level:(0 1 2 3 4 5)' \
  '1:DISPLAY (optional first arg; must start with ":"):'
